  "text": {
    "title": "Unit Two: Definite and Indefinite Articles",
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "The Definite Article",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "id": 1,
            "content": "The **definite article** in Italian corresponds to the English **the**. Unlike English, the Italian definite article changes according to the **gender**, **number**, and **initial letter(s)** of the noun it accompanies. The forms of the definite article are: **il**, **lo**, **l’**, **la** (for **singular** nouns); **i**, **gli**, **le** (for **plural** nouns)."
          },
          {
            "id": 2,
            "content": "**Il** is used before **masculine singular** nouns beginning with a **consonant**, except those beginning with **s + consonant**, **z**, **gn**, **ps**, **pn**, **x**, or **y**:",
            "table": {
              "headers": null,
              "rows": [
                ["**il libro**", "book"],
                ["**il tavolo**", "table"],
                ["**il cane**", "dog"],
                ["**il ragazzo**", "boy"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": 3,
            "content": "**Lo** is used before **masculine singular** nouns beginning with **s + consonant**, **z**, **gn**, **ps**, **pn**, **x**, or **y**:",
            "table": {
              "headers": null,
              "rows": [
                ["**lo studente**", "student"],
                ["**lo zucchero**", "sugar"],
                ["**lo gnomo**", "gnome"],
                ["**lo psicologo**", "psychologist"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": 4,
            "content": "**L’** is used before **masculine** or **feminine singular** nouns beginning with a **vowel**:",
            "table": {
              "headers": null,
              "rows": [
                ["**l’amico** [m]", "friend"],
                ["**l’amica** [f]", "friend"],
                ["**l’uomo** [m]", "man"],
                ["**l’ora** [f]", "hour"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": 5,
            "content": "**La** is used before **feminine singular** nouns beginning with a **consonant**:",
            "table": {
              "headers": null,
              "rows": [
                ["**la casa**", "house"],
                ["**la ragazza**", "girl"],
                ["**la scuola**", "school"],
                ["**la porta**", "door"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": 6,
            "content": "**I** is used before **masculine plural** nouns beginning with a **consonant**, except those beginning with **s + consonant**, **z**, **gn**, **ps**, **pn**, **x**, or **y**:",
            "table": {
              "headers": null,
              "rows": [
                ["**i libri**", "books"],
                ["**i tavoli**", "tables"],
                ["**i cani**", "dogs"],
                ["**i ragazzi**", "boys"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": 7,
            "content": "**Gli** is used before **masculine plural** nouns beginning with **s + consonant**, **z**, **gn**, **ps**, **pn**, **x**, **y**, or a **vowel**:",
            "table": {
              "headers": null,
              "rows": [
                ["**gli studenti**", "students"],
                ["**gli zuccheri**", "sugars"],
                ["**gli gnomi**", "gnomes"],
                ["**gli amici**", "friends"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": 8,
            "content": "**Le** is used before all **feminine plural** nouns, regardless of their initial letter:",
            "table": {
              "headers": null,
              "rows": [
                ["**le case**", "houses"],
                ["**le ragazze**", "girls"],
                ["**le scuole**", "schools"],
                ["**le amiche**", "friends"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": 9,
            "content": "Here is a summary of the definite articles:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["", "Singular", "Plural"],
              "rows": [
                ["Before consonant (except s + cons., z, gn, ps, pn, x, y)", "**il** (m), **la** (f)", "**i** (m), **le** (f)"],
                ["Before s + cons., z, gn, ps, pn, x, y", "**lo** (m)", "**gli** (m)"],
                ["Before vowel", "**l’** (m/f)", "**gli** (m), **le** (f)"]
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "title": "The Indefinite Article",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "id": 10,
            "content": "The **indefinite article** in Italian corresponds to the English **a** or **an**. It is used only with **singular** nouns and changes according to the **gender** and **initial letter(s)** of the noun. The forms are: **un**, **uno**, **una**, **un’**."
          },
          {
            "id": 11,
            "content": "**Un** is used before **masculine** nouns beginning with a **consonant** (except **s + consonant**, **z**, **gn**, **ps**, **pn**, **x**, **y**) or a **vowel**:",
            "table": {
              "headers": null,
              "rows": [
                ["**un libro**", "a book"],
                ["**un tavolo**", "a table"],
                ["**un cane**", "a dog"],
                ["**un amico**", "a friend"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": 12,
           0 "content": "**Uno** is used before **masculine** nouns beginning with **s + consonant**, **z**, **gn**, **ps**, **pn**, **x**, or **y**:",
            "table": {
              "headers": null,
              "rows": [
                ["**uno studente**", "a student"],
                ["**uno zucchero**", "a sugar"],
                ["**uno gnomo**", "a gnome"],
                ["**uno psicologo**", "a psychologist"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": 13,
            "content": "**Una** is used before **feminine** nouns beginning with a **consonant**:",
            "table": {
              "headers": null,
              "rows": [
                ["**una casa**", "a house"],
                ["**una ragazza**", "a girl"],
                ["**una scuola**", "a school"],
                ["**una porta**", "a door"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": 14,
            "content": "**Un’** is used before **feminine** nouns beginning with a **vowel**:",
            "table": {
              "headers": null,
              "rows": [
                ["**un’amica**", "a friend"],
                ["**un’ora**", "an hour"],
                ["**un’arancia**", "an orange"],
                ["**un’idea**", "an idea"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": 15,
            "content": "Here is a summary of the indefinite articles:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["", "Masculine", "Feminine"],
              "rows": [
                ["Before consonant (except s + cons., z, gn, ps, pn, x, y)", "**un**", "**una**"],
                ["Before s + cons., z, gn, ps, pn, x, y", "**uno**", "-"],
                ["Before vowel", "**un**", "**un’**"]
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "title": "Notes on Usage",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "id": 16,
            "content": "Unlike English, the **indefinite article** is often omitted in Italian when the noun refers to a **profession**, **nationality**, or **religion**, unless it is qualified by an adjective:",
            "table": {
              "headers": null,
              "rows": [
                ["**È medico**", "He/she is a doctor"],
                ["**È italiano**", "He is Italian"],
                ["**È cattolico**", "He/she is Catholic"],
                ["**È un medico famoso**", "He/she is a famous doctor"],
                ["**È un italiano gentile**", "He is a kind Italian"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": 17,
            "content": "The **definite article** is used in Italian in some cases where it is omitted in English:",
            "list": [
              "Before **abstract nouns**: **La felicità è importante** (Happiness is important).",
              "Before **plural nouns** used in a general sense: **I libri sono utili** (Books are useful).",
              "Before **days of the week** to mean ‘every’: **Il lunedì lavoro** (I work every Monday).",
              "Before **languages** (except after ‘parlare’): **Il francese è bello** (French is beautiful).",
              "Before **parts of the body** or **possessions** instead of possessive adjectives: **Mi fa male la testa** (My head hurts)."
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
